#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:-1
msgid ""
"Define named compiler sets (toolchains) in Spack to easily and consistently "
"apply compiler choices for C, C++, and Fortran across different packages."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:13
msgid "Toolchains (toolchains.yaml)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:15
msgid ""
"Toolchains let you group a set of compiler constraints under a single, user-"
"defined name. This allows you to reference a complex set of compiler choices "
"for C, C++, and Fortran, with a simple spec like ``%my_toolchain``. They are "
"defined under the ``toolchains`` section of the configuration."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:21
msgid ""
"The sections :ref:`language-dependencies` and :ref:`explicit-binding-"
"virtuals` provide more background on how Spack handles languages and "
"compilers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:24
msgid "Basic usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:26
msgid ""
"As an example, the following configuration file defines a toolchain named "
"``llvm_gfortran``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:28 ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:80
#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:120
msgid "``~/.spack/toolchains.yaml``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:28
msgid ""
"toolchains:\n"
"  llvm_gfortran:\n"
"  - spec: cflags=-O3\n"
"  - spec: \"%c=llvm\"\n"
"    when: \"%c\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%cxx=llvm\"\n"
"    when: \"%cxx\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%fortran=gcc\"\n"
"    when: \"%fortran\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:41
msgid ""
"The ``when`` clause in each entry determines if that line's ``spec`` is "
"applied. In this example, it means that ``llvm`` is used as a compiler for "
"the C and C++ languages, and ``gcc`` for Fortran, *whenever the package uses "
"those languages*. The spec ``cflags=-O3`` is *always* applied, because there "
"is no ``when`` clause for that spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:45
msgid "The toolchain can be referenced using"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:47
msgid "$ spack install my-package %llvm_gfortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:51
msgid "Toolchains are useful for three reasons:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:53
msgid ""
"**They reduce verbosity.** Instead of multiple constraints ``%c,cxx=clang "
"%fortran=gcc``, you can simply write ``%llvm_gfortran``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:55
msgid ""
"**They apply conditionally.** You can use ``my-package %llvm_gfortran`` even "
"if ``my-package`` is not written in Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:57
msgid ""
"**They apply locally.** Toolchains are used at the level of a single spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:64
msgid "Pitfalls without toolchains"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:66
msgid ""
"The conditional nature of toolchains is important, because it helps you "
"avoid two common pitfalls when specifying compilers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:68
msgid ""
"Firstly, when you specify ``my-package %gcc``, your spec is "
"**underconstrained**: Spack has to make ``my-package`` depend on ``gcc``, "
"but the constraint does not rule out mixed compilers, such as ``gcc`` for C "
"and ``llvm`` for C++."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:70
msgid ""
"Secondly, when you specify ``my-package %c,cxx,fortran=gcc`` to be more "
"explicit, your spec might be **overconstrained**. You not only require "
"``gcc`` for all languages, but *also* that ``my-package`` uses *all* these "
"languages. This will cause a concretization error if ``my-package`` is "
"written in C and C++, but not Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:75
msgid "Combining toolchains"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:77
msgid ""
"Different toolchains can be used independently or even in the same spec. "
"Consider the following configuration:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:80
msgid ""
"toolchains:\n"
"  llvm_gfortran:\n"
"  - spec: cflags=-O3\n"
"  - spec: \"%c=llvm\"\n"
"    when: \"%c\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%cxx=llvm\"\n"
"    when: \"%cxx\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%fortran=gcc\"\n"
"    when: \"%fortran\"\n"
"  gcc_all:\n"
"  - spec: \"%c=gcc\"\n"
"    when: \"%c\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%cxx=gcc\"\n"
"    when: \"%cxx\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%fortran=gcc\"\n"
"    when: \"%fortran\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:101
msgid "Now, you can use these toolchains in a single spec:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:103
msgid "$ spack install hdf5+fortran%llvm_gfortran ^mpich %gcc_all"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:107
msgid "This will result in:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:109
msgid ""
"An ``hdf5`` compiled with ``llvm`` for the C/C++ components, but with its "
"Fortran components compiled with ``gfortran``,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:110
msgid ""
"Built against an MPICH installation compiled entirely with ``gcc`` for C, C+"
"+, and Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:113
msgid "Toolchains for other dependencies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:115
msgid ""
"While toolchains are typically used to define compiler presets, they can be "
"used for other dependencies as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:117
msgid ""
"A common use case is to define a toolchain that also picks a specific MPI "
"implementation. In the following example, we define a toolchain that uses "
"``openmpi@5`` as an MPI provider, and ``llvm@19`` as the compiler for C and "
"C++:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:120
msgid ""
"toolchains:\n"
"  clang_openmpi:\n"
"  - spec: \"%c=llvm@19\"\n"
"    when: \"%c\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%cxx=llvm@19\"\n"
"    when: \"%cxx\"\n"
"  - spec: \"%mpi=openmpi@5\"\n"
"    when: \"%mpi\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:132
msgid ""
"The general pattern in toolchains configuration is to use a ``when`` "
"condition that specifies a direct dependency on a *virtual* package, and a "
"``spec`` that :ref:`requires a specific provider for that virtual <explicit-"
"binding-virtuals>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:134
msgid ""
"Notice that it's possible to achieve similar configuration with :doc:"
"`packages.yaml <packages_yaml>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:136
msgid "~/.spack/packages.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:136
msgid ""
"packages:\n"
"  c:\n"
"    require: [llvm@19]\n"
"  cxx:\n"
"    require: [llvm@19]\n"
"  mpi:\n"
"    require: [openmpi@5]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:147
msgid ""
"The difference is that the toolchain can be applied **locally** in a spec, "
"while the ``packages.yaml`` configuration is always global. This makes "
"toolchains particularly useful in Spack environments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:151
msgid "Toolchains in Spack environments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:153
msgid ""
"Toolchains can be used to simplify the construction of a list of specs for "
"Spack environments using :ref:`spec matrices <environment-spec-matrices>`, "
"when the list includes packages with different language requirements:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:155
msgid "spack.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:155
msgid ""
"spack:\n"
"  specs:\n"
"  - matrix:\n"
"    - [kokkos, hdf5~cxx+fortran, py-scipy]\n"
"    - [\"%llvm_gfortran\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:164
msgid ""
"Note that in this case, we can use a single matrix, and the user doesn't "
"need to know exactly which package requires which language. Without "
"toolchains, it would be difficult to enforce compilers directly, because:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:167
msgid "``kokkos`` depends on C and C++, but not Fortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:168
msgid "``hdf5~cxx+fortran`` depends on C and Fortran, but not C++"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:169
msgid "``py-scipy`` depends on C, C++, and Fortran"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../toolchains_yaml.rst:173
msgid ""
"Toolchains are currently limited to using only direct dependencies (``%``) "
"in their definition. Transitive dependencies are not allowed."
msgstr ""
